I've always been a caring and unselfish person, its how I was raised and its how my family operates. With the conditions of the last few months, with my romantic partner suffering from a severe depression and a suicidal episode, my ability to put him first has helped him and kept our relationship together. It has allowed me to do things that I enjoy and has helped me pursue and plan my future career. My two worst qualities kind of compliment my best qualities. I have trouble putting myself first when others are in need and forget that I need things as well. This also makes my self-esteem suffer, and I don't take care of any of it so it just tends to get worse until I can realize what's wrong.

column130: My intelligence is one of my best traits because it helps me most significantly throughout my life so far. Not only is this intelligence in a book-wise sense, but I am also relatively sharp and able to think on my feet. This lends itself well to flexibility and adaptability, which are two of my stronger traits. I also chose boldness because I stand up for what I believe in and tend to have a fuck-all attitude when it comes to people trying to resist against progressive change.  I chose insensitivity because I think I sometimes say things to people without thinking about the impact of what I am going to say. For example, I should keep my mouth shut, but I end up saying more information than I should.  Absentmindedness falls into this same category.

column130: Because I make friends easily. Pretty much outgoing. But can never get what I want from others. Bad at any interpersonal circumstances.

Aware is one of my best traits because it helps me sense how I am feeling and how others are feelings. I am also conscious of my actions and what may be causing me to act a certain way. I am also very organized which keeps me on task and others as well.   On the flip side, while I believe being organized is one of my better traits, it also evolves sometimes into one of my worst. I become too structured and planned at times. Anxiety plays a big role in my life and sometimes brings out my worst qualities.

column130: I am funny because my jokes are laughed at - I'm considered a funny guy and I like that I'm funny. I think my curiosity has helped me become a better student and a better lab technician. I'm always ready to learn something new and I'm not someone who wants to just sit back and do nothing.  However I'm always anxious that I'm making mistakes - that I'm not being the best I could be. Maybe there's something I'm forgetting, something I could do better. And even when things are going well, a lot of the times, I feel unsatisfied, almost as if I feel like I don't deserve the good that is happening to me. These traits take up most of my time and many times it's pretty depressing.

column130: I picked good listener and personable as my best traits because they are things that I have found help my relate to others better. People usually come to me for advice because I am personable and approachable and they know I will listen to their problem or rant and give good advice. I like being the person people come to with their problems so that's why I choose these as my best traits.   My worst traits I chose because I don't really like them about myself. I now have the ability to step back and evaluate a situation to see how my actions and behaviors influence the reactions of others. Impulsivness is one of my worst traits because it often gets me in trouble when I act without thinking first. This most often occurs when I am angry, but also in instances where I fail to consider the consequences of my actions. I will sometimes try and justify my impulsive actions by reasoning that the rules don't apply to me or thinking that someone deserves a thorough rebuke because they are inherently lesser than me. These justifications are the manifestations of a sometimes arrogant personality, another poor trait of mine.

column130: I consider loyal on my strongest attributes in the sense that I am consitent. If I say I will do this or be somewhere I make sure that I follow through with that. I think it also helps a lot in being a good friend because being a reliable/consistent is necessary. The same is true for work and work relationships. I listed being objective as the other positive trait because currently there are several high-profile and controversial events in the media (Michael Brown and Eric Granger). In these situations and all others that might come up being able to want to at least try and understand someone's perspective ESPECIALLY if it differs from your own is so necessary in not only keeping the peace, but also avoiding a one-track mind.   For negative attributes I listed being scatter brain and being stubborn. I listed being scatter-brain is an issue beause it allowed me to get very easily side-tracked. So though I may have good intentions about doing this or following up with others it is quite easy for me to forget or overlook something unintentionally. The stubborn is the other negative attribute becuase though sometimes I have taken time to hear something, but am very slow to accept.

column130: I think I am known for making friends easily and getting along with people really well, and I think it is because I'm easygoing and have a sense of humor. People like talking to you if you can make a joke and handle taking one. Procrastination is one of my worst traits because I know I can do a lot better in school if I just worked harder. One of my greatest fears is rejection so a lot of times I try to be noncommittal. That way I'm not the one getting hurt.

Some people think I am pretty funny and I have been called nice one too many times. I have been labelled the nice guy by a lot of people. However, I am well aware that I have confidence issues and that I don't trust people easily.

The reason that I mentioned the capacity to think deep and my ability to be aware of my feelings and behaviors is because I feel that enables me to take responsibility for my own behavior. I do not blame others for the way I feel or act and the awareness enables me to take corrective action. The fact that I needed close to 20 minutes to come up with these two traits is providing me with more food for thought on how much of my mind and life is still left to be examined. Laziness is my worst quality since it is the main reason for the difference between where I ought to be and where I am. Distraction comes a close second because it prevents me from doing things the way I want to be doing. Be it while studying or looking for a job.

I think of myself as dedicated because I'm incredibly committed to the the things I commit my time and effort to. I spend countless hours for organizations I've invested in, work incredibly hard in school to do my best, and stay dedicated to my friends who are close to me. I also think I try to be kind to everyone. This one isn't incredibly deep or requiring of a long explanation; I just try to be kind.  Stress is something I struggle with a lot, which can be a negative consequence of my dedication. I often find myself with entirely too much on my plate, and not willing to sacrifice anything to prioritize. I sometimes unintentionally inflict this stress on those around me when I try to take on too much and struggle to accomplish it all. I also don't think I'm very confident. Especially surrounded by such intelligent peers, I struggle to see myself as smart or good at the things I do. I'm quick to criticize my own work and have a hard time gracefully accepting a compliment.

My mood swings dominate my life, and many people have told my that my flakiness bothers them and so both of those things are traits I need to work on. But i have very strong empathy and I view all things in life through an artistic lens, and those two qualities are some of the things that set me apart from others in a positive way. Even though being extremely empathetic is often extremely painful.

column130: I'm consistently told by people that I am very kind and that's why I'm easy to get along with. I have become friends with people who aren't used to being treated well by their other friends and they tell me that they appreciate how I treat them. I don't see any reason to be anything but kind to people. There is no point in being rude or unnecessarily mean to someone even when you are frustrated because it will never accomplish anything productive. I believe that people are inherently kind but continuous negative interactions with others who have treated them poorly may have led them to become defensive and not expect people to treat them with respect. My parents raised me to be kind to everyone I meet and that is something I will carry with me forever. Kindness comes easily but patience is something I have had to learn over time. Most people generally expect immediate results or get upset if things don't go their way the first time but I have learned that persistence and patience will lead to better results. I have also learned that being patient with people will lead to strengthened relationships. I haven't been in any "fights with any of my friends since I was very young because we've all learned that outbursts and giving each other the cold shoulder until someone gives in is not the way to solve problems. Giving each other breathing room and talking things out is the preferable solution. I admire people who are patient and understanding most of the time and I strive to be that way too. I think that my biggest insecurities stem from past relationships and friendships which were unhealthy and led me to doubt myself in ways that I rationally know that I shouldn't. The rational side of me knows that I am worthy and my thoughts and opinions are valid and important but sometimes a large part of me doubts all of that. In class I am often too nervous to raise my hand and share my ideas even though I know that contributing what I think will help the discussion progress. However, my insecurities sometimes drag me down and it is difficult to overcome them. Another insecurity that I've carried with me since I was very young is insecurity with my weight. Although I am of a normal and healthy weight for my age and height now, I used to be slightly overweight as a child and people's comments have stuck with me for over a decade. I can usually ignore them and am relatively happy with my appearance but sometimes I have bad days or weeks when I can't shake the feeling that I need to lose weight to be beautiful.  Not standing up for myself is something that I am still working on overcoming. I have gotten a lot better at this throughout my time here at school but sometimes I still struggle to let people know when they are doing something that is making me feel uncomfortable. In order to avoid conflict I'll often not bring up things that my roommates are doing that are really bothering me. For example, I took out the trash almost every time for the entire first semester of this year because neither of my roommates wanted to. I was usually the first to give in because I hate not cleaning up after myself or seeing trash pile up. Near the end of the semester I decided I wasn't going to take it out so I waited. One of my roommates ended up calling me out and saying that we can't keep waiting until the other person caves and that she would take it out this time but we would have to take turns from then on. This infuriated me but I still did not say anything about it to anyone. After that I made sure to bring up the topic to them and now we're on a cycle where we take turns every time. It's been working very well. I wish I would've done it sooner though and although I am proud of myself I still wish I was better at standing up for myself.  Another example is that my best friend from here who is also one of my roommates has an incredibly extroverted personality. She does not have a lot of close friends because she often comes off as too aggressive and overly opinionated. She's turned out to be one of the best friends I've ever had because once she lets down her wall she's actually an incredibly kind and caring person. However, sometimes she does say things that she shouldn't say to me or does things that hurt my feelings and although I have gotten better at not taking it to heart it is still difficult for me to tell her how I feel when she says those things. It's something I will continue to work on and grow with.

I believe that I am especially driven because I am extremely passionate about certain issues and I want to devote my life to working on those issues. Because of this everything that I do, I commit my self to whole heartedly. I have a vision of where I want to be and I see every decision that I make as getting me closer towards achieving that goal.  I also think that I am a good listener because I really enjoy helping people with their problems. I care about the people that I talk to and I invest myself in their lives. I hope that people can come to me with issues and know that I will lend my ears.

I can cook alright.  Nothing exceptional, but enough to keep the table interesting day to day, and be relatively healthy.  Mostly Korean and Japanese cuisine though.  I guess I make killer steaks too, but I rarely do it.   (get it.. rarely... ) I think this is a very important trait.  I've always put great value on the culinary culture, and I'm kind of proud at how good my food is.  Really.    I took a year off school to work last year.  Working, I've gained many new skills, perhaps most important of which is goog - I mean problem solving.   I became an excellent problem solver with the tools at my disposal (internet/google). I believe this is a beneficial skill to have anywhere.   It was actually more difficult to come up with these this time around, than my past PAIRS surveys.  I'm not sure why.  Last year was a rather large turning point for me.  I took a year off from school and worked my butt off.  went from an office paper boy to assistant operations manager in one year.  It was crazy, I learned so much, and changed considerably as a person.   I don't like to say it this way (because it's not exactly accurate) but it helped me overcome my depression.  mature a bit, maybe.  But the more I grow older, the less I seem to be really sure of who I really am, and what "personality traits" I lock into.   What are my best qualities?  who knows?    I'm still lazy.  Really lazy.  that's just bad, no arguments there.
column132: positive, forward thinking, willing to live a little
column133: dead on the inside and outside
column134: yes. I did in my previous response.  I took a year off school, got a job at a small start-up engineering company.  worked like crazy.  made some money.  Learned a ton.

column130: I might not be nice to everyone I meet, but I am kind, and I go out of my way to help people and make sure that people in my community are okay. I like that about myself, and I think it speaks to a good core. Being a good friend is very important to me, and I think my loyalty helps keep me grounded, and helps me understand other people better.  It's interesting because I feel like I'm both arrogant and that I have a high level of self-doubt, which probably requires some cognitive dissonance on my part. My arrogance makes me defensive, which makes it harder for me to listen to other people's ideas, which is bad, and I'm very sensitive to the implication that others think less of me for any reason. I think that makes me difficult to like all the time, and difficult to give honest constructive criticism. My self-doubt makes me even more sensitive to criticism, and exacerbates my anxiety/depression because I always manage to convince myself that I'm behind, and that everyone is better at everything than I am. It makes me overly competitive, and again, not very pleasant to be around.

I heard I'm friendly and easy to talk to from other people, but considering how I don't feel like that's my "true" personality since I'm very reserved and usually pretty apathetic towards others, it's a bit of an act I guess. I think truly I'm pretty selfish, but I just hide it well.

I work diligently to finish a job once I have started it. I refuse to give up, which helps me accomplish my goals and makes me a strong asset to a team. I am also a highly authentic individual; I recognize who I am as a person and will not compromise my personal values to suit others' expectations. Staying true to myself and what I believe is very important to me.  In large groups, I can be quiet and reserved. Thus, it has been difficult for me to find a romantic partner because I am most comfortable around my close friends. I also can become anxious easily and respond to stress in my environment, which can be aggravating to myself and others.

column130: In my opinion, I wouldn't be able to survive at WashU without tenacity and openness. My tenacity has allowed me to keep up with the workload from my studies, extracurricular activities, and personal projects. I have always tried to maintain my work ethic, and I think that it has paid off. As far as openness, I feel as though life is an adventure, and it is this attitude that has kept me wanting to learn more.  For introversion and lack of confidence, that's simple. I'm in the business school and I need to constantly make a good impression in front of my peers and participate in class. My general anxiety and tendency to want to be alone sometimes has gotten in the way of these requirements. As a good example, earlier this semester I had to speak in front of about 50 important people. I was so nervous that my legs almost couldn't hold the weight of my body.

column130: I am a person who can always be relied on to get work done. When in group settings or on my own, everything that I must complete is always completed. Depending on how important to me it is, I may not do it right away, but I definitely always follow through. I am also incredibly hardworking. I do my best to make sure that everything I do is done to the very best of my abilities. I spend hours and hours working for the student newspaper each week to make sure that it comes out as a good reflection on the whole staff. I am someone who doubts myself a lot. I have a terrible image of myself--I see myself as very unattractive and annoying at times. I am constantly worried that people don't like me or are judging me. Logically I understand that this isn't true, but that is how I feel, and I haven't been able to change that. I also suffer from recurring depression. Though I am not in a terribly bad place right now, I always fear falling back into that hole. I spent the majority of my second semester last year severely depressed, and much of high school as well.

column130: I would say I am a dependable and helpful person because I care for my friends and the important people in my life and make sure that I am available to them if they need help or someone to lean on. If I care about a person, I go out of my way to make them happy. Are they my best qualities? I'm not sure but I have had people tell me that I am helpful or dependable so those came to my mind first.  I would say that 'emotional' and 'worry a lot' are my worst qualities because I always end up getting hurt and overthinking things to the point that I get anxious or depressed. And I also get emotionally vulnerable and this leads to me getting hurt by people even more.

Who doesn't like an optimistic person?  This world is so tough with bad things happening to everyone - so it's nice to have someone look at the upside when everything seems to be falling down.  It helps me stay upbeat and enthusiastic.    Loyalty is huge to me as a value.  I am loyal to my friends and to my family.  I am loyal to my beliefs.  But mostly being loyal to my friends and family gives them someone who will always be there for them.  When times get tough, they can count on this little doobie.

I think that my intelligence drives a lot of my personality. I am passionate about learning and creating and thinking. I like to read and write and paint. These are the things that really make me feel alive. I think my intelligence also drives my humor which is how I relate to others. My authenticity is something that I'm really working on and have been over the past year. After I lost my brother last year it just seemed really futile and counter-productive to keep trying to make everything seem perfect.  My depression and anxiety are very intrinsic to my personality. I don't see them so much as disorders but as part of me, even though that kind of sucks. I have become incredibly pessimistic and jaded at a young age, perhaps because of the vast amount of traumatic events that have taken place in my life. Strangely enough, though, my depression really fuels a lot of my creativity and reflection.

column130: I tend to be one to give people 2nd, 3rd, 4th, etc. chances before I write them off as a person and friend.  Therefore, I believe myself to be forgiving. Additionally, I like to be non-judgmental and open-minded when interacting with others, which I think is a positive quality. In terms of worst qualities, I find that when something negative occurs I tend to have a strong surge of emotions and sometimes act impulsively on those emotions without thinking about the consequences.  Usually I don't do anything too drastic, but I sometimes say things that I shouldn't.

column130: Loyalty is one of my best qualities because it helps me make wonderful friendships and relationships. I tend to drift away from friendships and relationships that aren't fully satisfying, and without my loyalty I don't think I could find them. Optimism is my other best quality because it not only keeps me motivated, I think I help others see the beauty in the world sometimes.   Being judgmental is by far my worst quality because it pushes me away from people that I barely know. However, I feel that I'm not always wrong and it's kept me from bad situations. However, I definitely find fault in others a lot faster than I find fault in myself. Being lazy is another bad quality because even though I am motivated to accomplish my goals, and I know that I will, I feel that I could be so much more successful and accomplish so much more if  I did things like wake up earlier or increase my curiosity.

I believe that my most important role right now is "student." On top of that, though, I have a myriad of other roles to fulfill as well. There are a lot of things to juggle right now - work and school and friendships and plays and other extra curriculars. Being able to handle all those things (lacking sleep), and being able to do so without losing my mind is important. I have to stay calm and take things one at a time, because I can't afford to drop the ball, and I'd like to maintain some illusion of sanity while I'm at it.  I think what I'm most unhappy about right now are my relationships. I find it very difficult to make close friends rather than acquaintances, and I think part of that is because I am shy. And I get so excited to meet someone with whom I seem to click despite my shiness (someone who might be a romantic interest), that I force myself to open up too quickly - and I get played. It's happened often enough this past year that I can see myself becoming more shy and withdrawn - for fear of being fooled again - and I can't stop it.

column130: I believe one of my best qualities is my reliability. If asked to complete a task or meet with someone, I have a strong motivation to follow through on these plans. One of my other best qualities is kindness because I make an effort to understand the circumstances of others and offer them support when I can. I prefer being agreeable, and even when I encounter someone whose opinion is very different from mine, I would prefer having a discussion and being polite rather than arguing with them.  In turn, this preference also reflects that I am somewhat timid. Since I prefer keeping peace, I avoid speaking up or being assertive when necessary. I worry that what I have to say might be wrong or challenged in a way in which I cannot offer an intelligent response, so I often hesitate and choose not to aggravate an issue. Another of my worst qualities is that I can be indecisive and a bit of a perfectionist. Perhaps I have a desire to please everyone and I worry that my choices won't be accepted. However, I also think a considerable part of this might be my own high expectations for myself.

i enjoy supporting people and being able to be a reliable confidant to others. I want to be helpful and see myself in a loyal and honest role in helping a person, even a stranger. I also enjoy knowing what is going on the in the world, who it may affect, and how to better understand those affected. I acknowledge the privilege I have from my background and my family, and it is my duty as a member of a wider community to better understand those without that privilege. I want to know how i can help rather than be on the side that hurts.  I am extremely quick to see the parts of people that may turn out to be not favorable to me. I am quick to judge, and assign how i feel about people before I actually know who they are. i need to work on enhancing my worst traits rather than settling for them as the norm.

column130: I am patient and nice when I know people need my help to accomplish something or need a favor.  I am moody and irritable when my living situation is out of my control and my suitemates leave everything messy and chaotic.

column130: I am doing well in math subjects so I think I am intelligent. I am kind to people around me.   Even though I am able to figure out many difficult problems, I sometimes make very stupid calculation mistake.  When I am in an unfamiliar situation, I will tend to be nervous.

I tend to be very empathetic towards others and aim to treat them well. It generally manifests in how I endeavor to remember details and struggles of other people's lives and try to help them through difficult times, and how when I can sense someone else feels uncomfortable about something I work to reassure them and make them feel welcome and accepted.  However, I feel that how I act outwardly and some of my inner thoughts are sometimes disconnected. I can be quite judgmental and jump to conclusions quickly about people, which is something that I try to never let affect how I treat anyone. Nevertheless I can sometimes think some rather terrible things initially (I'm very reactionary that way).

column130: Although I'm optimistic, I balance it out with being realistic. My optimism allows me to see the positive possible outcomes of a situation that may not be the best. I'm extremely encouraging toward my friends which has led to more self encouragement.  I'm doing it less often but I frequently make self disparaging comments, sometimes in order to make people laugh and sometimes because I don't think highly of myself. I also can get very nervous/anxious.

I chose being compassionate as being one of my best qualities because it helps me be more understanding of others. Rather than automatically assuming someone is "finally showing their true colors" or is simply a bad and/or lazy person, being compassionate allows room for other stories. Maybe someone is just having a bad day or is simply not doing well, and that is okay. It doesn't mean something terrible is wrong with them or that they're the scum of the earth. Similarly, being attentive allows me to quickly realize if someone is in a bad spot and perhaps needs some help or encouragement. It's easy to brush small stuff off, but sometimes a well-timed compliment or a genuine "How are you?" can go a long way. It also keeps me in touch with my own feelings and thoughts. I chose nervousness as one of my worse traits because it prevents me from fully enjoying my experiences with other people. I get caught up thinking about the impression I'm making or how I look to others or if I'm being understood, and it can be difficult to fully process what my conversation partner is trying to communicate. In a related manner, negativity can hinder my growth by causing me to avoid my flaws or issues by denying their existence. Rather than address problems, I'd prefer to bypass the negative feelings associated with them by putting them away. Negativity can also color my interactions in a bad way, whether past or present.
column132: aware of my own motives and intentions.
column133: consumed with work and worry about academics.
column134: I am currently residing in another country.

column130: I believe that I am both intelligent and compassionate and that these two traits are my best characteristics.  I chose intelligence because I have always relied upon being smart as a defining a large portion of my personality. More importantly than that, however, is the idea that my intelligence (coupled with hard work, of course) will be able to get me where I want to go in life.  I feel that by being smart when I was younger, I was given opportunities that even kids at my school weren't, and this in turn helped me get to where I am today.  On the other hand, I chose compassionate as my second important trait because I feel as though this also plays a large part in helping me get where I want to go in the future.  Aloofness causes me to have trouble connecting with others and my stubbornness sometimes inhibits my ability to have an open mind and to engage in productive discussions with others.

column130: I'm more interested in helping others on a daily basis. I generally prioritize other peoples needs over mine and I feel like it's better to be giving than getting and it makes me very happy when the people i've helped succeed. It makes it all worth it.  I have been dropped from a friend group recently and it is really hard to forgive them for all of the unkind things they've done to me because they are also my teammates so I have to be around them a lot. I also rely heavily on first impressions and generally dislike people that are too outgoing. I easily find flaws in people and base my whole judgment on them.

I have a lot of friends who tell me I seem very confident, and I myself consider that to be a positive quality. It's also one of my favorites parts of me. The same goes with my sass. Confidence also spreads to all areas of my life. I'm very rarely insecure about anything because of this. I don't care if I'm not the most attractive or have the best grades because I am confident in my own abilities and know what I am capable of. My sass is more of my sense of humor. It's the 'maybe what she's saying is offensive, but I can't be sure because she's saying it with a smile' kind of humor.  I have also been told I can be cold and rude at time. This what it seems like because I am not afraid to tell people what I think of them, and they often do not like my honesty. I also often don't have patience for the emotions of others, which is why I seem cold. The rudeness however comes from my assertiveness. If someone wants me to do something I don't want to do, I'll tell them I don't want to do it. For example, one of my friends has a minuscule role in a play about black oppression in the 1950's and wanted us to see her in it. I however did not want to watch a four hour play about black oppression in the 1950's when my friend has a single line in it, so I told her that in slightly nicer words.

I consider myself to be an smart person and my intelligence allows me to succeed in school and socially. I think that because I'm considerate, I'm very aware of how the people around me are thinking and feeling and I try really hard to put people at ease and make them feel good about themselves.  I can be internally judgmental of people, which means I make assumptions about people based on surface level impressions and don't take the time to get to know them, which isn't fair. I can be impatient if I feel that people aren't pulling their weight or performing at the standards I expect of myself, which means group work, for instance, can be stressful for me, even though I don't let others see my impatience.

column21: 11228 Island Lakes Lane Boca Raton, FL 33498
column130: Empathy and resilience are my two best traits. Empathy allows me to help others, something that is incredibly important to me and which I am making a career out of. Being resilient is for me, and has helped me through some very tough times. These two things more than possibly anything else are my dominant personality traits, or at least I hope so.  My two worst qualities are definitely holding grudges, and possibly being impatient (though I think maybe being too sensitive or getting ticked off easily is closer?). But holding grudges has always been and is still something I want to improve on.
column134: Got accepted to graduate school, moved back to the USA

column130: Being creative is one of my best qualities because it doesn't have a negative counterpart. It's the source of some of my most appreciated skills--writing, drawing, quick thinking. It makes me wholly me and unique from others because even other creative people are different from each other. Being funny is one of my best qualities because it makes me likable and interesting. It helps cement friendships.  Being lazy is one of my worst qualities because it hinders me in a lot of aspects of my life. It hinders me from progressing creatively, intellectually, academically, physically among others. I feel like if I wasn't lazy, I could be such a better person. It sounds cliche to say I have potential but I know for sure I could be doing significantly better in all aspects of my life if I could overcome my laziness. Being unreliable is one of my worst qualities because it hurts my character or how others think of me. I become the friend that's expected to flake or the person that no one can put faith in completely to finish a task or do something.

I'm very smart, and sharp. I do well understanding new things. And when I do things I do them with my whole heart which is generally what makes me successful.  I sometimes see problems where they don't really exist, and therefore being dramatic leads to conflict with people. column130: Objectively speaking, I'm intelligent. Any test designed to measure intelligence would say so. It's the one quality I'm /sure/ I have and can rely on. Creativity has also always been a part of my life, and my (perhaps overly) active imagination has always tried to manifest itself. I've always felt a need to create, whether it be with Lego or in-class writing exercises as a kid, or music, poetry, and short stories now that I'm in college. My creativity and intelligence go hand-in-hand to help me with what I consider my best skill--writing poetry and fiction.  My entire life, I've been extremely quick to anger, and my emotions can change very quickly. I was extremely violent in elementary and middle school, and while I have mostly gotten my emotions under control today, I still get angry at computer problems very quickly, and can sometimes overreact to the things my friends say and do to me. At the same time, I can go from being in a perfectly normal mood one day to morbidly depressed the next, with absolutely no reason. When this happens, I can get angry at my friends even more easily than usual. Meanwhile, I seem to tire out all the people I talk to after just a few minutes, so I'm not certain if this is because I'm annoying or because I'm boring, but I would at least guess that it's one of these two. In any case, I tend not to make many new friends, and those that I do make tend not to stay friends for long.

column130: I am always able to bring enthusiasm to the table, whether it's in friendships, activities or work, and that is usually very good for me and those around me. I find things more interesting as a result, and life is a lot more fun if you get pumped about it. I think a lot of my friends enjoy my enthusiasm above all, and it's definitely a part of me that I feel strongly about as well. Though I'm never going to be the kindest person, the smartest person, or the most important person in the room, I can definitely be the most enthusiastic and can contribute to dynamic situations as such. I am also a very loyal person, and I believe very strongly that it is important to forge close relationships and keep them. Nowadays, people are less loyal than in the past, whether it's in marriages, workplaces, etc, probably because we have so much choice available to us. I think that it's rather sad, because the best relationships are often the ones you have to groom and work for over a long period of time. My most valuable friendships have also been those in which I have had disagreements or arguments; getting through the bad times and staying loyal to a person you know is your friend makes the relationship better.  I like to talk about myself too much, and I definitely spend too much time in my own head. It's better in relationships to be a good listener, but I instead have a tendency to be cocky and ramble on and on about my own successes, stories and achievements. I like to do so, and I like the admiration I get, but it's definitely not a trait that I'm proud of, and i try and keep my boasting to a minimum. I do think of myself too highly as well, especially since i know cognitively that I'm pretty average among my peers. I don't think of myself as better than others, but I often feel it.

column130: Insight: there have been times when I've brought my friends to tears of gratitude by sharing with them (eloquently) what most people assume is readily evident to them, and it seems to cause positive change in their lives (as focusing on strengths is wont to do). Also because I want to be the type of person that inspires others to be the best versions of themselves, it's very rewarding. ^_^ Empathy: Through persistently applying myself towards the goal of understanding people, I have found myself in positions where I have understanding for many sides of a battlefield and feel pain for each side's hurt, but also that they don't realize how similar they actually are, and with fair frequency that other people aren't actually disagreeing. Empathy helps me humanize, helps me have way more friends in the world than "enemies".  Energy: When I can't bring myself to accomplish any of the things I want to do with my life, let alone the insipid, tedious tasks of mundane life that help me accomplish those things, it's incredibly damaging to not just the short term tasks, but also my self-esteem and confidence in my ability to achieve, feeding together into a dark downward spiral. Self-discipline/focus: There's this... ability, this... stuff, that some types of people like entrepreneurs seem to have in droves, that allows them to keep pushing themselves towards their goals, despite all setbacks, distractions, deterrents, or erstwhile painfully unrelated but necessary tasks (cf. Energy above). It's self-discipline when it's choosing to do the necessary things, and it's focus when I'm doing any of the things and get distracted, but it seems to be the same stuff. And the thing is, having an organizational system, having external structure, would help with this area a ton, but I don't have that, either, so it's one of my biggest problem areas and sources of feeling ineffective.
